# Role Based Access Controls Lab
---

Q: Inspect the environment and identify the authorization modes configured on the cluster.
Check the kube-apiserver settings.

A: The kube-apiserver setting can be viewed from the manifest file for the kibe-apiserver 
pod. This is usually located under '/etc/kubernetes/manifests/kube-apiserver.yaml'. Locate 
this line '--authorization-mode=Node,RBAC' under 'command'.

---

Q: How many roles exist in the default namespace?

A: Run the command:

> kubectl get roles

---

Q: How many roles exist in all namespaces together?

A: Run:

> kubectl get roles --all-namespaces

---

Q: Check what are the resources a role called 'kube-proxy' in the 'kube-system' namespace 
giving access to.

A: This can be done by describing the role:

> kubectl describe role kube-proxy -n kube-system

---

Q: Which account is the kube-proxy role assigned to?

A: Run:

> kubectl get rolebindings.rbac.authorization.k8s.io --all-namespaces -o wide

---

Q: A user dev-user is created. User's details have been added to the kubeconfig file. Inspect the permissions granted to the user. Check if the user can list pods in the default namespace.

A: To run a command as the dev-user you can do the following:

> kubectl get pods --as dev-user

---

Q: Create the necessary roles and role bindings required for the dev-user to create, list and delete pods in the default namespace.

A: You can view details on creating a role in the terminal by running:

> kubectl create role --help

Example:

> kubectl create role developer --verb=list,create,delete --resource=pods

or to just get the manifest object run:

> kubectl create role developer --verb=list,create,delete --resource=pods --dry-run=client -o yaml > developer-role.yaml

The role manifest file can be viewed in the yamls folder. The bind the role you can get 
information for the command with this:

> kubectl create rolebinding --help

Example:

> kubectl create rolebinding dev-user-binding --role=developer --user=dev-user

Or you can run the command in dry mode and get the manifest for it with this:

> kubectl create rolebinding dev-user-binding --role=developer --user=dev-user --dry-run=client -o yaml > dev-user-binding.yaml

The manifest can be viewed in the yamls directory: /yamls/dev-user-binding.yaml.

